thanks Dave, the beginPos will change for each call of this method. It is the region index of the first region of a group of regions.
 If a table has 28 regions, and Trafodion decides to start 4 ESPs for this query, each ESP then needs to handle 7 regions. So the first ESP will be responsible for region 0 - 6, second 7- 13, etc... So the beginPos will be 0, 7, 14, 21 . I am not sure if hash will generate same value for this sequence?
Even so, in fact, which regionserver is most popular for a given range, for example, 0 -7, it is already  random. This randomization is an attempt, if it doesn't work as we wish, it doesn't harm, and we can continue to design some new algorithm,

Ming: It looks like what happened is Aven developed her work on her master branch, and the first few commits are merges from the origin/master branch to bring it up-to-date. (You can look at these by clicking on the SHA code -- the 7-digit hex code -- given at the right of the commits.) The final result is just the one file change. I think all is well. 

Another way to develop code that doesn't require such merge commits is to create a fresh branch each time that tracks origin/master, and then discard that branch after the pull request is merged. That's the way recommended in the Trafodion Contributor's Guide.

Code changes look OK to me. A question: When would we set TRAF_UPSERT_WITH_INSERT_DEFAULT_SEMANTICS to 'ON'? Is this something that would be done under the covers by some utility, say, LOAD?

Non-aligned format tables

For a table having a column with current_timestamp, we had issues when this column was omitted in a upsert statement. It wouldn't put a cell with current timestamp into hbase table.Then, a wrong value for the timestamp is displayed when the row is selected. In addition, the raw hbase table would have cells for the omitted default value columns at times. It wasn’t consistent when the cell with default value is inserted into raw hbase table.

When there is a omitted COM_CURRENT_DEFAULT column, the upsert is changed to merge always.  All other times it would be just upsert/insert.  All other default columns when it is not user specified is not written to hbase table. It is resolved at the time of select using the default values.

Aligned format:
There was corruption in the aligned format table row because the omitted columns with default values were not populated correctly.

Fix:
By default, upsert is always is changed to merge.  If the row doesn’t exist,  a new row is inserted with omitted  default values filled in.  If the row exists, the omitted columns are filled with old values.

With the cqd TRAF_UPSERT_WITH_INSERT_DEFAULT_SEMANTICS set to ON the omitted columns will always be filled with default values when upserted.

Yes, It is possible that I can use the above CQD to avoid merge in case of non-aligned format. But to ensure that we get the default value when this CQD is set to ON, we need to store the default values always when omitted. We wouldn’t be able to take advantage of the feature of skipping cells when omitted and still get the default value upon select without actually storing the data in hbase.  Hence the above CQD applies to aligned format alone.

Merge is an expensive operation than just upsert/insert. If the user is ok to just to replace the default value for omitted columns or is sure that there wouldn't any matching row in the table, he/she can set this CQD to get better throughput numbers.
